.TH PS(1),User Commands,PS(1)

.SH NAME
ps - list running processes

.SH SYNOPSIS
ps [-aeh] [-p pid[,pid...]]

.SH DESCRIPTION
ps prints one line per process showing PID, instance ID, parent PID, and command name.

By default, ps lists only processes that share an ancestor with itself, so a ps run from a shell shows the shell and its descendants.
With -a or -e, every live process in the system is shown.
With -p, only the processes whose PIDs are listed are shown.

PIDs given to -p may be separated by commas or spaces.
PIDs are parsed as numbers in decimal, or in hexadecimal with a leading $ or 0x.

.SH OUTPUT
The first line is a header:

 PID  IID PPID CMD

PID is printed as a 3-digit decimal bank number.
IID is printed as 0xNN.
PPID is the parent PID in decimal.
CMD is the command name recorded for the process.

.SH OPTIONS
-a, -e: List all processes in the system.

-p pid[,pid...]: List only the named processes.
Overrides the default ancestor filter.

-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
ps: unknown option -- X - an unrecognised flag was given.

ps: option requires an argument -- X - -p was given with no argument.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Listing completed.

1: An unknown option was given or -p was missing its argument.

.SH SEE ALSO
kill(1), top(1)
